div.p:
Being the most popular CI/CD tool,
Jenkins in an open-source automation
server in which the central build and
continuous integration process take
place. It is a self-contained Java-based
program with packages for Windows,
macOS, and other Unix-like
operating systems. It supports
master - slave architecture and
parallelism.

Gitlab ecosystem is one of the
most powerfuls Source Code
Management tool out there, Gitlab
has it's own CI/CD tool. Using
yaml playbooks, Gitlab code's can
be easily manageable with all
the tracking and insights
features that Gitlab provides.

Team City and Travis CI. One of
its most powerful features is the
pre-environment permissions
that allow developers and testers
to deploy to their environments
on-demand while the production
stays locked down

Jenkins is the most popular CI/CD tool out there, it means, it has a huge
community and documentation. Is always free, and for environments that
can have a dedicated host for CI it's always the best choose. Also, plugins
are easy to manage.

div.p:
Circle CI is a CI/CD tool that also
allows automation from code
building, testing to deployment.
But different than Jenkins, Circle CI
implements yaml playbooks, that
might be easier to implement.
Also, is not needed to have a
dedicated server for using it. It's
highly customizable and low
maintenance needed.

div.p:
Very similar to Circle CI, Team City is a
cloud-based tool supported by JetBrains.
One of it most useful features is the
build tracking, it means, we can run
historical builds and view test history
reports. Also, it's able to run parallel
builds simultaneously on different
environments. Another good feature is
the re usage of setting and confs between
parent and childs projects.

div.p:
Travis CI is another web-based tool
for CI/CD which support a lot of
different languages and integrates
a bunch of tools for testing and
recreating databases. Is not
as popular as other tools, but is still
used.

div.p:
CI Tools like Jenkins, Travis CI,
Circle CI, and others, allow
developers to create deliver or
deploy pipelines for the builded
artifact at continuous stage.
However, there are a lot more
of CD tools specialized on only
CD, meaning they probably
have better features for all the
CD process.

div.p:
Harness is a Cloud Provider CD tool,
It leads the pack when it comes to
governance with fine-grained Role
Base Access Control, full audit trails,
and proprietary integrated secrets.
It’s also worthy to note the incredibly
easy installation.

div.p:
Argo CD is the cream of the
open-source crop. This feature-rich
solution automates Kubernetes
deployments using GitOps technology
and supports a wide variety of config
management tools, SSO integrations,
and webhook integrations.
Argo CD’s stated goal is to make
application deployments automated,
auditable, and easy to understand.

Despite the large number of options, Jenkins is the best option for small
projects, which not expect a lot of security features, auditability, and also
is probably one of the best options for All at Once deployments or Basic
deployments, which not need human verifications for it's deployments and
complex features.
